From: OpenBook Maintainers <goodhackersolutions@gmail.com>
Date: Sun, 8 Jun 2026 00:00:04 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 5/6] features: recognize bundled OpenBook system extensions

SPDX-License-Identifier: MPL-2.0

Hook so the three first-party OpenBook extensions are recognized and allowed by
the build as bundled/built-in extensions:
  - vault-ui@openbook.browser      (lock screen / cryptographic-lockout UI)
  - proxy-manager@openbook.browser (proxy switching + fail-closed leak UI)
  - ai-sidebar@openbook.browser    (opt-in AI assistant, OFF by default)

This registers their install location so packaging can drop the built XPIs into
the application's bundled-extensions directory and the front-end treats them as
first-party. ExtensionSettings in config/policies/policies.json additionally
allowlists these IDs at the policy layer.

This is only the build/recognition hook; the extensions themselves live in
extensions/ and are built separately. AI stays OFF by default with no host
permissions until the user opts in (invariant #5).

NOTE: exact hunk context is rebased in CI against Firefox 145.0.2.
---
 toolkit/mozapps/extensions/internal/builtinExtensions.json | 15 +++++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 15 insertions(+)

diff --git a/toolkit/mozapps/extensions/internal/builtinExtensions.json b/toolkit/mozapps/extensions/internal/builtinExtensions.json
index 9999999..aaaaaaa 100644
--- a/toolkit/mozapps/extensions/internal/builtinExtensions.json
+++ b/toolkit/mozapps/extensions/internal/builtinExtensions.json
@@ -1,2 +1,17 @@
 [
+  {
+    "id": "vault-ui@openbook.browser",
+    "location": "app-builtin",
+    "base": "resource://openbook-vault-ui/"
+  },
+  {
+    "id": "proxy-manager@openbook.browser",
+    "location": "app-builtin",
+    "base": "resource://openbook-proxy-manager/"
+  },
+  {
+    "id": "ai-sidebar@openbook.browser",
+    "location": "app-builtin",
+    "base": "resource://openbook-ai-sidebar/"
+  }
 ]
